We apply our proposed Homogenization Index to classify embedding tables into three categories, as detailed in Table II. These categories correspond to large, medium, and small error bounds, denoted as L, M, and S, respectively. In Table III and Table IV, we select some representative EMB Table to show how Homo Index ranking achieves EMB Table Classification.

Compression Performance across Embedding Tables.
Furthermore, we outline the compression ratios our compressor achieved across various embedding tables and delve into the data characteristics that enable our compressor to secure maximum compression benefits.
Table V presents the compression ratios for various compressors across different embedding tables. We can draw three key observations from this result. Firstly, the compression ratios for all compressors vary significantly across embedding tables, underscoring the importance of choosing a compressor that’s well-suited for each specific table. Secondly, our optimized vector-based LZ algorithm excels with certain embedding tables, while its performance on others is less impressive. Lastly, the performance trends of our optimized entropy-based compressor and the vector-based LZ algorithm appear to be in stark contrast.
